Thus much has been said with the view of in- ducing to the study of Moral Philosophy. We have spoken of it as a science with whose general scope and functions our readers are supposed to be familiar3 but we propose to consider briefly one or two points, which would be useful to any one taking up the study without much opportunity of direction, and which may serve as a nucleus to his enquiries.
